<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1901-07-27T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1901-07-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="294" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d294">
                    <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Rockhill</persName> to Mr.
                                <persName type="to">Hay</persName>.</hi></head>
                    <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg></opener>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1901-07-27"><hi rend="italic">July 27,
                            1901</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                    <p>(Mr. Rockhill reports that the application of the new tariff immediately
                        after signing the protocol, only exempting goods in transit, is favored by a
                        majority of the diplomatic corps. In view of the abolition of the free list,
                        he has raised an objection, suggesting a delay of three months.</p>
                    <p>Instructions requested.)</p>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>